        {"id": "r_c1_2", "level": "C1", "target_band": 7.5, "passage": "The phenomenon of linguistic relativity, often associated with the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis, posits that the language we speak influences the way we think and perceive the world. While strong versions of this hypothesis—suggesting language determines thought—have been largely discredited, more nuanced interpretations acknowledge that language can subtly shape cognitive processes. For instance, speakers of languages with different spatial reference systems have been shown to differ in their approaches to navigation and memory tasks, suggesting that linguistic categories may indeed have cognitive consequences, albeit less deterministic than once proposed.", "question": "What is the current scholarly view on linguistic relativity?", "options": ["A) It has been completely proven", "B) Strong versions are rejected, but subtle influences are recognized", "C) It has no scientific basis", "D) It only applies to spatial concepts"], "correct": "B"},
